	# [6h] https://www.linkedin.com/learning/paths/foundational-math-for-machine-learning
		What you will learn:
		    Master linear algebra fundamentals.
		    Grasp calculus concepts for machine learning.
		    Harness the power of probability in machine learning.
		    Unlock insights with statistical analysis.
		[1h30] https://www.linkedin.com/learning/machine-learning-foundations-linear-algebra
		[1h30] https://www.linkedin.com/learning/machine-learning-foundations-calculus
		[1h30] https://www.linkedin.com/learning/machine-learning-foundations-probability/probability-for-machine-learning
			Learning objectives:
			    Define and explain the concept of probability and its application in real-world scenarios.
			    Describe the difference between probability and likelihood in mathematical terms.
			    Identify and interpret basic probability concepts: experiment, sample space, and event.
			    Compute probabilities using different probability rules such as complement rule, addition rule, and multiplication rule.
			    Distinguish between discrete and continuous random variables and their probability distributions.
			    Apply the binomial, Bernoulli, and Poisson distributions to model real-world situations.
			    Evaluate and explain the Central Limit Theorem and its significance in machine learning.
			    Utilize histograms to represent probability distributions and determine patterns in data.
			    Analyze the use of Bayes' Theorem in practical applications, including Naive Bayes classifiers.
			    Develop understanding of the role and application of probability distributions in machine learning models.
		[1h30] https://www.linkedin.com/learning/machine-learning-foundations-statistics
			Learning objectives:
			    Apply measures of central tendency and variability in a dataset.
			    Interpret the purpose of standard error from sample data.
			    Analyze the meaning of negative correlation.
			    Recognize correlation coefficient values and relationships.
			    Identify probability and distributions in statistical analysis.
			    Evaluate the purpose of bootstrapping in statistical analysis.

